TY  - JOUR
AU  - Campbell, John
AU  - Deaton, Angus
T1  - Why is Consumption So Smooth?
PY  - 1989
Y1  - 1989/07/01
DO  - 10.2307/2297552
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 56
IS  - 3
SP  - 357
EP  - 373
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - For thirty years it has been accepted that consumption is smooth because permanent income is smoother than measured income. This paper considers the evidence for the contrary position, that permanent income is in fact less smooth than measured income, so that the smoothness of consumption cannot be straightforwardly explained by permanent income theory. The paper argues that in postwar U.S. quarterly data, consumption is smooth because it responds with a lag to changes in income.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2297552
ER  - 



